{"priority": "major", "kind": "bug", "repository": {"links": {"self": {"href": "data/repositories/osrf/gazebo.json"}, "html": {"href": "#!/osrf/gazebo"}, "avatar": {"href": "data/bytebucket.org/ravatar/{51a0cd5d-8697-4eb1-8b08-e919ee881e1c}ts=1694483"}}, "type": "repository", "name": "gazebo", "full_name": "osrf/gazebo", "uuid": "{51a0cd5d-8697-4eb1-8b08-e919ee881e1c}"}, "links": {"attachments": {"href": "data/repositories/osrf/gazebo/issues/2058/attachments_page=1.json"}, "self": {"href": "data/repositories/osrf/gazebo/issues/2058.json"}, "watch": {"href": "https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/osrf/gazebo/issues/2058/watch"}, "comments": {"href": "data/repositories/osrf/gazebo/issues/2058/comments_page=1.json"}, "html": {"href": "#!/osrf/gazebo/issues/2058/use-clock_monotonic-in-sleep-and-timer"}, "vote": {"href": "https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/osrf/gazebo/issues/2058/vote"}}, "reporter": {"display_name": "Steve Peters", "uuid": "{2ccfed09-18b8-4921-8d58-15ef01092802}", "links": {"self": {"href": "https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/users/%7B2ccfed09-18b8-4921-8d58-15ef01092802%7D"}, "html": {"href": "https://bitbucket.org/%7B2ccfed09-18b8-4921-8d58-15ef01092802%7D/"}, "avatar": {"href": "data/secure.gravatar.com/avatar/1fb4816dad9e68337d3096f750951f6cd=httpsavatar-management--avatars.us-west-2.prod.public.atl-paas.netinitialsSP-1.png"}}, "nickname": "Steven Peters", "type": "user", "account_id": "557058:5de38267-b118-494c-aa76-4fab35448816"}, "title": "Use CLOCK_MONOTONIC in Sleep and timer functions", "component": {"name": "common", "links": {"self": {"href": "data/repositories/osrf/gazebo/components/138866.json"}}}, "votes": 0, "watches": 1, "content": {"raw": "The `Time::Sleep` function on Linux uses [clock_nanosleep(CLOCK_REALTIME, ...)](#!/osrf/gazebo/src/73fae73d688a67241403ed58636f5da0fd72e314/gazebo/common/Time.cc?fileviewer=file-view-default#Time.cc-427), which is based on the system clock, which can jitter if changed by ntp ([see stackoverflow](http://stackoverflow.com/a/3527632)). Using `CLOCK_MONOTONIC` would provide more consistent timing.\r\n\r\nIssueForNewDevelopers", "markup": "markdown", "html": "<p>The <code>Time::Sleep</code> function on Linux uses <a data-is-external-link=\"true\" href=\"#!/osrf/gazebo/src/73fae73d688a67241403ed58636f5da0fd72e314/gazebo/common/Time.cc?fileviewer=file-view-default#Time.cc-427\" rel=\"nofollow\">clock_nanosleep(CLOCK_REALTIME, ...)</a>, which is based on the system clock, which can jitter if changed by ntp (<a data-is-external-link=\"true\" href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/a/3527632\" rel=\"nofollow\">see stackoverflow</a>). Using <code>CLOCK_MONOTONIC</code> would provide more consistent timing.</p>\n<p>IssueForNewDevelopers</p>", "type": "rendered"}, "assignee": null, "state": "resolved", "version": null, "edited_on": null, "created_on": "2016-09-29T01:15:58.186457+00:00", "milestone": null, "updated_on": "2018-12-16T05:40:32.825518+00:00", "type": "issue", "id": 2058}